    <div class="faq-container">
      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What is JEPQ dividend yield and how is it calculated?</summary>
        <p>JEPQ dividend yield is currently 11.39%, calculated by dividing the annualized distribution amount ($6.16) by the current share price ($54.13). This yield includes both dividend income from underlying stocks and option premium income from the covered call strategy. The yield fluctuates based on share price movements and distribution amounts.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How has JEPQ dividend history performed since inception?</summary>
        <p>JEPQ dividend history shows consistent monthly distributions since May 2022. The fund has paid out over $16 per share cumulatively, with monthly amounts ranging from $0.34 to $0.62. Annual totals have grown from $3.65 in 2022 (partial year) to $6.29 in 2025, demonstrating the fund's ability to generate reliable income through various market cycles.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>When does JEPQ pay dividends and what are the key dates?</summary>
        <p>JEPQ pays dividends monthly, typically around the first week of each month. The ex-dividend date is usually the last business day of the prior month, with record date one day later. For example, for March distributions, the ex-dividend date would be around February 28th, with payment in early March. Always check official JPMorgan announcements for exact dates.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How does JEPQ compare to JEPI in terms of dividends?</summary>
        <p>JEPQ typically offers higher dividend yields than JEPI (11.39% vs 7-8%) because it focuses on the more volatile Nasdaq 100 versus JEPI's S&P 500 approach. JEPQ's tech-heavy concentration generates higher option premiums but comes with increased volatility. JEPI offers more stability and consistent distributions, while JEPQ provides higher income potential with growth exposure.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What drives JEPQ dividend amounts and distribution variability?</summary>
        <p>JEPQ dividend amounts are driven by two sources: dividends from underlying Nasdaq 100 stocks and premiums from selling covered calls. Distribution amounts vary based on implied volatility levels (higher volatility = higher option premiums), market performance, and the fund's active management decisions. Tech sector earnings seasons and major market events can impact monthly distribution amounts.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Are JEPQ dividends qualified for tax purposes?</summary>
        <p>JEPQ dividends include both qualified dividends from underlying stocks and non-qualified income from option premiums. The option premium portion (majority of the distribution) is typically taxed as ordinary income at your marginal tax rate, not the lower qualified dividend rate. Consider holding JEPQ in tax-advantaged accounts like IRAs to maximize after-tax income.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>Can I reinvest JEPQ dividends and what's the benefit?</summary>
        <p>Yes, most brokers offer dividend reinvestment plans (DRIP) for JEPQ. Reinvesting allows you to purchase additional shares with your monthly distributions, compounding your income over time. With JEPQ's 11.39% yield, reinvestment can significantly accelerate wealth building through the power of compound returns, especially in tax-deferred accounts.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>What are the risks of relying on JEPQ dividends for income?</summary>
        <p>Key risks include: distribution cuts if market volatility decreases (reducing option premiums), higher volatility than traditional dividend stocks, concentration risk in tech sector, and tax inefficiency in taxable accounts. The covered call strategy also caps upside during strong bull markets. Diversification across multiple income sources is recommended for income-dependent investors.</p>
      </details>

      <details class="faq-item">
        <summary>How sustainable are JEPQ's high dividend payments?</summary>
        <p>JEPQ's dividend sustainability depends on continued volatility in the Nasdaq 100, which historically has been higher than broader market indices. The fund's active management and the tech sector's inherent volatility support the strategy, but distributions could decline if volatility drops significantly or if tech stocks enter a prolonged low-volatility environment. The 374% payout ratio indicates distributions exceed traditional earnings metrics.</p>
